      <div class="prose">

        <div class="verdict">✓ Updated April 2026</div>

        <p>Framing contractors work at the intersection of speed and precision. A framing crew can spend tens of thousands of dollars in lumber and hardware on a single house. Estimating errors become expensive quickly. Scheduling errors ripple through every trade that follows — plumbing, electrical, HVAC can't start until framing is complete, so a two-day framing delay becomes a two-week schedule impact by project end.</p>

        <h2>What framing contractors need from software</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Lumber takeoff:</strong> Accurate board foot calculations from plans, by species and dimension</li>
          <li><strong>Material scheduling:</strong> Lumber orders must arrive before the crew, not after — delivery timing coordination</li>
          <li><strong>Crew management:</strong> Assign lead framers to jobs, track crew hours against bid</li>
          <li><strong>GC schedule integration:</strong> Know when your start date is firm and what your completion commitment is</li>
          <li><strong>Job costing:</strong> Lumber cost per square foot of floor area is the key efficiency metric to track</li>
          <li><strong>Change orders:</strong> Plan changes mid-frame are common; capturing extra work and re-materials promptly is critical</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Lumber takeoff: the core challenge</h2>
        <p>Accurate lumber takeoff from residential plans requires counting studs, plates, headers, rafters, joists, sheathing, and hardware for each framing assembly. Getting this right is the difference between a profitable job and one that barely breaks even. Options:</p>

        <h3>Manual takeoff with PlanSwift</h3>
        <p>Experienced framers can use PlanSwift's linear and count measurement tools to take off wall lengths, opening counts, and floor areas, then apply their own framing factor formulas. This requires an experienced estimator who knows the regional framing practices, but produces accurate results for contractors who have the estimating knowledge.</p>

        <h3>Framing-specific estimating software</h3>
        <p>Platforms like Framecad and Virtek (more common in commercial metal framing) provide automated framing takeoff and engineering. For residential wood framing, the traditional approach of experienced manual takeoff or specialized framing estimating spreadsheets remains common. Contractors who've developed their own takeoff methodology over years often find it difficult to match the accuracy of their own systems with general-purpose tools.</p>

        <h2>Best software picks for framing contractors</h2>

        <h3>As a sub on residential projects: Buildertrend</h3>
        <p>Framing subs working under residential GCs increasingly need to work within the GC's project management platform. Buildertrend is the most common platform for residential GCs. Subcontractors receive free portal access — you can see your scheduled start date, access drawings, review your scope of work, submit daily logs, and communicate with the GC, all without a subscription fee. Being fluent with Buildertrend is a competitive advantage when GCs are selecting framers.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
