        <h3>For framing GCs: JobTread or Contractor Foreman</h3>
        <p>Framing contractors who self-perform as GC (hiring their own crews and managing the full framing package including engineering and labor) need project management tools. JobTread and Contractor Foreman both handle estimates, schedules, POs for lumber, and crew management at reasonable price points.</p>

        <h3>For commercial framing: Procore</h3>
        <p>Commercial light-gauge steel framing contractors working on commercial projects will typically interface with Procore or Autodesk Build through the GC's platform. Managing RFIs, submittals (shop drawings for engineered header and beam specifications), and daily reports through the GC's platform is standard for commercial work.</p>

        <h2>Coordinating with lumber suppliers</h2>
        <p>Framing is one of the most material-dependent trades. Lumber orders must be coordinated precisely with delivery timing:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sequence orders:</strong> Sill plates and first-floor framing delivered before second-floor material</li>
          <li><strong>Lead time awareness:</strong> Engineered lumber (LVL beams, I-joists) often has 2–3 week lead times — order early</li>
          <li><strong>Delivery confirmation:</strong> Confirm delivery timing 24–48 hours before pour — lumber deliveries on wrong days create major field disruption</li>
          <li><strong>Backorder management:</strong> Know your substitution options before you need them</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Change order management for framers</h2>
        <p>Mid-frame changes are common: structural revisions from the engineer, owner-requested additions, MEP coordination changes that require framing modifications. Capturing these as change orders — rather than absorbing them as "part of the job" — is where framing contractors protect their margins. Good construction software makes generating a change order as easy as a few taps on a phone, so it actually gets done rather than forgotten in the rush of framing activity.</p>

        <h2>Key metrics to track</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Labor hours per 100 SF of floor area:</strong> Benchmark your crews against historical performance</li>
          <li><strong>Lumber cost per SF:</strong> Actual vs. estimated, by job type</li>
          <li><strong>Cycle time:</strong> Days to frame a house of a given plan (by plan type)</li>
          <li><strong>Waste percentage:</strong> Actual lumber waste vs. budgeted waste factor</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Bottom line</h2>
        <p>Framing contractors primarily working as subs on residential projects benefit most from being comfortable with Buildertrend (the GC platform), combined with their own estimating approach (PlanSwift or a proven framing takeoff spreadsheet). Framing GCs managing crews and subcontracts should add JobTread or Contractor Foreman for project management.</p>

